So this is Nathan.

00:00:06.290 --> 00:00:09.490
And he is the co-founder
and Creative Director

00:00:09.490 --> 00:00:11.890
at "Roadtrip Nation."

00:00:11.890 --> 00:00:16.266
And he started his first road
trip back in 2001, I believe.

00:00:16.266 --> 00:00:17.140
NATHAN GEBHARD: 2001.

00:00:17.140 --> 00:00:19.720
FEMALE SPEAKER: So he's going
to tell you a little bit more

00:00:19.720 --> 00:00:22.610
about his current
book, "Roadmap."

00:00:22.610 --> 00:00:27.140
And he has a few co-authors
with them today as well.

00:00:27.140 --> 00:00:28.860
We'll go through
his presentation.

00:00:28.860 --> 00:00:31.320
If you have questions,
there's time at the end.

00:00:31.320 --> 00:00:33.960
And then there's books
available for a book signing.

00:00:33.960 --> 00:00:36.970
And you can come talk to him
and the other authors as well.

00:00:36.970 --> 00:00:37.980
So thank you.

00:00:37.980 --> 00:00:39.440
NATHAN GEBHARD: Sweet.

00:00:39.440 --> 00:00:40.910
Well, thanks for
coming, you guys.

00:00:40.910 --> 00:00:42.140
I'm going to kind
of just walk you

00:00:42.140 --> 00:00:43.598
guys through the
story of "Roadtrip

00:00:43.598 --> 00:00:46.320
Nation" and our new book.

00:00:46.320 --> 00:00:49.270
And as Caroline said before,
we've got a few co-authors here

00:00:49.270 --> 00:00:50.030
that will join us.

00:00:50.030 --> 00:00:52.420
So Alyssa, Jamie,
Willie, and Annie

00:00:52.420 --> 00:00:55.520
will come up on to the
stage for the Q&amp;A part.

00:00:55.520 --> 00:01:00.260
So just to give you a
little sense of "Roadtrip."

00:01:00.260 --> 00:01:02.650
When people ask,
what is "Roadtrip",

00:01:02.650 --> 00:01:06.710
what do you guys do, this
is the simple sentence.

00:01:06.710 --> 00:01:08.400
We create experiences
that empower

00:01:08.400 --> 00:01:11.160
individuals to build livelihoods
around their interests.

00:01:11.160 --> 00:01:14.830
And I think it took us a while
to put that sentence together

00:01:14.830 --> 00:01:16.650
and to really feel
comfortable with it

00:01:16.650 --> 00:01:19.190
because I think the underlying
piece is that it really

00:01:19.190 --> 00:01:23.310
came from a much more rough and
uncertain question, which was,

00:01:23.310 --> 00:01:24.880
what am I going to
do with my life?

00:01:24.880 --> 00:01:28.980
So in 2001, myself and two other
co-founders, Mike and Brian,

00:01:28.980 --> 00:01:31.310
were about ready to
graduate from college

00:01:31.310 --> 00:01:33.030
and just realized we
were sitting there

00:01:33.030 --> 00:01:35.680
in a situation where the lives
that we were about to lead

00:01:35.680 --> 00:01:36.630
were not our own.

00:01:36.630 --> 00:01:41.770
So Mike was a double major--
biology kinesiology major.

00:01:41.770 --> 00:01:44.700
He had always thought he
was going to be a doctor.

00:01:44.700 --> 00:01:48.480
His entire family was
a family of doctors.

00:01:48.480 --> 00:01:51.450
And through one internship,
he realized he hated hospitals

00:01:51.450 --> 00:01:54.140
and that that was just
not going to be his life.

00:01:54.140 --> 00:01:58.770
Brian was about to become
third generation in a family

00:01:58.770 --> 00:01:59.320
business.

00:01:59.320 --> 00:02:02.600
So he was able to
look at his dad

00:02:02.600 --> 00:02:04.790
and see what life would
be like 20 years from now.

00:02:04.790 --> 00:02:06.206
He was able to
look at his grandpa

00:02:06.206 --> 00:02:08.139
and see what life
was like in 40 years.

00:02:08.139 --> 00:02:14.050
And so those two were in a very
similar situation as I was.

00:02:14.050 --> 00:02:16.890
I was really interested in--
I wouldn't even say art,

00:02:16.890 --> 00:02:19.080
but just being creative.

00:02:19.080 --> 00:02:22.410
But I had this inability to
articulate what being creative

00:02:22.410 --> 00:02:23.990
meant to an occupation.

00:02:23.990 --> 00:02:28.210
And so when I told my parents,
I want to do something creative.

00:02:28.210 --> 00:02:32.120
The only thing I could get
out of my mouth was painter.

00:02:32.120 --> 00:02:34.220
And that was the
only artsy people

00:02:34.220 --> 00:02:36.170
that I was exposed
to in my community.

00:02:36.170 --> 00:02:42.050
And I remember my parents just
totally like, yeah, you're

00:02:42.050 --> 00:02:44.720
going to be poor and homeless
and live under the boardwalk

00:02:44.720 --> 00:02:45.840
if you're a painter.

00:02:45.840 --> 00:02:48.730
And I used to think that that
was really a painful comment.

00:02:48.730 --> 00:02:50.690
But now that I really
reflect back on it,

00:02:50.690 --> 00:02:54.090
it was so accurate because
I'm a horrible painter.

00:02:54.090 --> 00:02:56.860
I really can't-- my six-year-old
daughter can paint much better

00:02:56.860 --> 00:02:59.300
than I can.

00:02:59.300 --> 00:03:01.847
It was just that I didn't
understand how to articulate

00:03:01.847 --> 00:03:02.680
something different.

00:03:02.680 --> 00:03:05.032
And so when I was
looking at school,

00:03:05.032 --> 00:03:06.990
was looking at trying to
figure out what to do,

00:03:06.990 --> 00:03:10.110
I just totally abandoned that
interest in being creative.

00:03:10.110 --> 00:03:14.392
And I listened to that societal
expectation of be successful.

00:03:14.392 --> 00:03:15.850
And I majored in
business because I

00:03:15.850 --> 00:03:17.350
thought that's what
you're supposed to do.

00:03:17.350 --> 00:03:19.266
Just go do something
that makes a lot of money

00:03:19.266 --> 00:03:20.640
and you'll be fine.

00:03:20.640 --> 00:03:24.710
And it was about the time when
I was getting ready to graduate.

00:03:24.710 --> 00:03:26.140
I was literally
just a few months

00:03:26.140 --> 00:03:27.820
from becoming the
consultant, which

00:03:27.820 --> 00:03:29.580
was like the assembly
line of everybody

00:03:29.580 --> 00:03:32.690
in my business major
were consultants.

00:03:32.690 --> 00:03:34.327
And I realized at
a career fair when

00:03:34.327 --> 00:03:35.910
I was passing out
my resume that I had

00:03:35.910 --> 00:03:37.930
no idea what a consultant does.

00:03:37.930 --> 00:03:40.570
And so I asked this
guy, like, hey,

00:03:40.570 --> 00:03:42.370
could I just take
you out to lunch

00:03:42.370 --> 00:03:46.386
and learn about what this thing
is that I'm about to become?

00:03:46.386 --> 00:03:48.260
And the only thing I
remember from that lunch

00:03:48.260 --> 00:03:50.000
is he was wearing a suit.

00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:52.400
And obviously by my
dress today, suits

00:03:52.400 --> 00:03:56.090
do not connect with who
I am as an individual.

00:03:56.090 --> 00:03:59.800
My blood was draining the entire
lunch because I just realized

00:03:59.800 --> 00:04:02.730
this whole thing
that I had expected

00:04:02.730 --> 00:04:05.200
that was easy to answer at
the family barbecue of like,

00:04:05.200 --> 00:04:07.470
I'm going to be a consultant.

00:04:07.470 --> 00:04:09.110
All of that just withered away.

00:04:09.110 --> 00:04:12.414
And so Mike, Brian, and myself
all had this instant moment

00:04:12.414 --> 00:04:13.830
right about the
time of graduation

00:04:13.830 --> 00:04:15.700
where we just
realized this is not

00:04:15.700 --> 00:04:17.980
going to work for ourselves.

00:04:17.980 --> 00:04:21.014
And so when we talked
about what are we

00:04:21.014 --> 00:04:22.930
going to do with our
lives, the answer to that

00:04:22.930 --> 00:04:23.750
was really simple.

00:04:23.750 --> 00:04:27.210
It was just, we've got to talk
to people that have already

00:04:27.210 --> 00:04:28.310
figured it out.

00:04:28.310 --> 00:04:31.100
Who out there has combined
interests and actually

00:04:31.100 --> 00:04:32.840
figured out a life
that they love?

00:04:32.840 --> 00:04:35.910
And so we literally just
thought, let's travel around

00:04:35.910 --> 00:04:37.540
the country.

00:04:37.540 --> 00:04:38.350
How do we do that?

00:04:38.350 --> 00:04:39.370
We can't afford hotels.

00:04:39.370 --> 00:04:40.300
Cool, we'll get an RV.

00:04:40.300 --> 00:04:44.000
So this is our
beat-up 1985 green RV.

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:47.840
We painted it green with
paint from Home Depot that

00:04:47.840 --> 00:04:48.670
was on sale.

00:04:48.670 --> 00:04:50.640
We literally just rolled it on.

00:04:50.640 --> 00:04:53.770
It's just caked over the
blinker lights and everything.

00:04:53.770 --> 00:04:56.217
It really was unsafe.

00:04:56.217 --> 00:04:57.800
And then we started
just cold-calling.

00:04:57.800 --> 00:04:58.880
We had no connections.

00:04:58.880 --> 00:05:01.587
The idea was just anybody
who sounded interesting,

00:05:01.587 --> 00:05:02.670
we wanted to talk to them.

00:05:02.670 --> 00:05:06.080
And we spent about almost a
year putting this road trip

00:05:06.080 --> 00:05:08.230
together, just sitting
at mom and dad's house,

00:05:08.230 --> 00:05:10.180
cold-calling all day long.

00:05:10.180 --> 00:05:12.240
So I booked an interview
with Sandra Day O'Connor

00:05:12.240 --> 00:05:16.010
from the 1-800 number on the
tours and information website

00:05:16.010 --> 00:05:17.250
for the Supreme Court.

00:05:17.250 --> 00:05:19.920
I cold-called Michael
Dell from the 1-800 number

00:05:19.920 --> 00:05:24.080
on a commercial where you're
supposed to buy your computer.

00:05:24.080 --> 00:05:26.160
My fax cover sheet
was my face placed

00:05:26.160 --> 00:05:28.750
against the glass of
the copy machine--

00:05:28.750 --> 00:05:32.480
to Michael Dell-- just trying
to stand out in some silly way.

00:05:32.480 --> 00:05:34.750
Mike called the director
of "Saturday Night Live"

00:05:34.750 --> 00:05:36.890
every three days
for three months

00:05:36.890 --> 00:05:39.330
until she finally
picked up, on stage

00:05:39.330 --> 00:05:42.620
getting ready for rehearsals
of the MTV Music Awards.

00:05:42.620 --> 00:05:45.170
And we just hounded all
of these different people

00:05:45.170 --> 00:05:47.100
that we thought were
really interesting.

00:05:47.100 --> 00:05:50.640
And that road trip was
really exceptional for us.

00:05:50.640 --> 00:05:53.040
It started as this
simple idea that we

00:05:53.040 --> 00:05:54.970
were going to try and
figure out our own life.

00:05:54.970 --> 00:05:57.610
But what changed was-- probably
two weeks into that road trip,

00:05:57.610 --> 00:05:58.860
we realized it was
so much different.

00:05:58.860 --> 00:05:59.651
It was much bigger.

00:05:59.651 --> 00:06:01.390
These conversations
that we were having

00:06:01.390 --> 00:06:03.200
needed to go beyond our lives.

00:06:03.200 --> 00:06:05.110
So from that first
road trip, we've

00:06:05.110 --> 00:06:08.470
been spending the last 15
years-- since 2001-- committed

00:06:08.470 --> 00:06:10.630
to this idea of sharing
with other people

00:06:10.630 --> 00:06:13.280
how other successful
individuals have defined

00:06:13.280 --> 00:06:15.000
their own roads in life.

00:06:15.000 --> 00:06:16.990
And so I want to
just walk you guys

00:06:16.990 --> 00:06:18.480
through how that's evolved.

00:06:18.480 --> 00:06:22.072
The first piece-- when we came
back, we had all this footage.

00:06:22.072 --> 00:06:23.280
We had never edited anything.

00:06:23.280 --> 00:06:24.710
We had never filmed anything.

00:06:24.710 --> 00:06:27.380
But we thought the best way
to share an experience is

00:06:27.380 --> 00:06:28.680
just to film it.

00:06:28.680 --> 00:06:31.180
So we learned how to
edit with a manual

00:06:31.180 --> 00:06:33.770
from Barnes &amp; Noble
on Final Cut Pro.

00:06:33.770 --> 00:06:39.070
We learned how to film
from people's advice.

00:06:39.070 --> 00:06:40.570
And ultimately,
that first road trip

00:06:40.570 --> 00:06:43.040
became a one-hour special
that we put together.

00:06:43.040 --> 00:06:48.960
It aired on maybe eight
public television stations.

00:06:48.960 --> 00:06:50.480
But it really started to grow.

00:06:50.480 --> 00:06:54.520
And so we decided in 2003
that we would shift and put

00:06:54.520 --> 00:06:55.565
other people on the road.

00:06:55.565 --> 00:06:56.940
So our road trip
was the only one

00:06:56.940 --> 00:06:58.245
we were in front of the camera.

00:06:58.245 --> 00:06:59.620
Every year after
that, we've been

00:06:59.620 --> 00:07:01.250
putting new groups
of road-trippers

00:07:01.250 --> 00:07:04.630
out to interview new people
who they really connect with.

00:07:04.630 --> 00:07:07.260
So this is just an example of
what it's evolved to today.

00:07:07.260 --> 00:07:10.190
We're in pre-production
on Season 13 of the series

00:07:10.190 --> 00:07:11.430
on public television.

00:07:11.430 --> 00:07:14.350
We've done 116 episodes so far.

00:07:14.350 --> 00:07:17.430
About 85 different road-trippers
have road-tripped with us.

00:07:17.430 --> 00:07:19.070
So it's been growing.

00:07:19.070 --> 00:07:23.760
We think we're in RV number
11 in terms of purchased,

00:07:23.760 --> 00:07:25.600
three currently working.

00:07:25.600 --> 00:07:27.680
The original RV is [? in ?]
our conference room.

00:07:27.680 --> 00:07:29.355
We had an RV in
Australia, New Zealand.

00:07:29.355 --> 00:07:34.470
We've done road trips in
Israel, all different places.

00:07:34.470 --> 00:07:38.532
This is the interview archive
that we've put together.

00:07:38.532 --> 00:07:39.990
So if you look at
that show, if you

00:07:39.990 --> 00:07:43.807
look at 116 episodes
of content, we really

00:07:43.807 --> 00:07:46.390
thought that there's got to be
a really dynamic way to explore

00:07:46.390 --> 00:07:47.760
this rather than just episodes.

00:07:47.760 --> 00:07:50.220
So we started to pull out
every single interview

00:07:50.220 --> 00:07:51.700
and put it up online.

00:07:51.700 --> 00:07:56.420
And so right now we've got
about 425 of the interviews

00:07:56.420 --> 00:07:59.010
that we've got up there, a
couple thousand videos all

00:07:59.010 --> 00:08:00.360
encompassed in that.

00:08:00.360 --> 00:08:03.390
And it's people from all
different walks of life.

00:08:03.390 --> 00:08:04.420
And we've got schools.

00:08:04.420 --> 00:08:07.910
In 2008 we started a nonprofit
that takes this content

00:08:07.910 --> 00:08:10.810
and turns it into curriculum
for high school students.

00:08:10.810 --> 00:08:14.060
And just to give you an idea
of the types of people that

00:08:14.060 --> 00:08:15.980
are in this archive--

00:08:15.980 --> 00:08:17.860
If you just think
about the Craigs,

00:08:17.860 --> 00:08:20.300
we interviewed
Craig Newmark, who's

00:08:20.300 --> 00:08:21.960
the founder of Craigslist.

00:08:21.960 --> 00:08:24.240
We interviewed Craig Brewer.

00:08:24.240 --> 00:08:27.340
He wrote and directed
the film "Hustle &amp; Flow."

00:08:27.340 --> 00:08:29.550
We interviewed Craig Venter.

00:08:29.550 --> 00:08:33.289
He is the guy who
decoded the human genome.

00:08:33.289 --> 00:08:38.480
And Craig Robinson, who's
the former educator,

00:08:38.480 --> 00:08:40.309
comedian on "The Office."

00:08:40.309 --> 00:08:42.429
So I wanted to
just show you guys

00:08:42.429 --> 00:08:44.164
what one interview looks like.

00:08:44.164 --> 00:08:46.580
This is an interview with a
team that we put on the road--

00:08:46.580 --> 00:08:48.110
actually from Oakland.

00:08:48.110 --> 00:08:51.130
You'll see them twice
in this presentation.

00:08:51.130 --> 00:08:54.120
And I think it's really exciting
to just look at one snippet.

00:08:54.120 --> 00:08:57.510
This is just three minutes
of Andrew Lins' story.

00:08:57.510 --> 00:08:59.289
And what you'll see
is a conversation

00:08:59.289 --> 00:09:00.080
that's much deeper.

00:09:00.080 --> 00:09:03.160
We're not asking him, how
much does a conservator make?

00:09:03.160 --> 00:09:04.580
What was your
necessary education?

00:09:04.580 --> 00:09:09.130
That stuff we can find
online thanks to Google.

00:09:09.130 --> 00:09:11.100
We wanted to know the
deeper questions, like,

00:09:11.100 --> 00:09:12.930
did you always know
what you wanted to do?

00:09:12.930 --> 00:09:15.560
How do you value
your sense of self?

00:09:15.560 --> 00:09:16.790
What did you do with risk?

00:09:16.790 --> 00:09:18.650
And how did you
find an occupation

00:09:18.650 --> 00:09:20.430
that relates to your interests?

00:09:20.430 --> 00:09:23.570
And so this is just a
little glimpse into one

00:09:23.570 --> 00:09:25.665
of our interviews.

00:09:25.665 --> 00:09:28.040
KISURA HENDRIX: I feel
like personal with this.

00:09:28.040 --> 00:09:29.290
Nobody gets to do this.

00:09:29.290 --> 00:09:30.610
ANDREW LINS: You're right.

00:09:30.610 --> 00:09:33.822
You're going to be one of
maybe 25 people to get up here.

00:09:33.822 --> 00:09:35.090
KISURA HENDRIX: Yeah.

00:09:35.090 --> 00:09:36.220
Isn't that cool?

00:09:36.220 --> 00:09:38.390
That's cool.

00:09:38.390 --> 00:09:40.835
And that's your job.

00:09:40.835 --> 00:09:45.202
And I think that's just
I think that's amazing.

00:09:45.202 --> 00:09:47.080
ANDREW LINS: When
I was your age,

00:09:47.080 --> 00:09:49.720
I was thinking of two careers.

00:09:49.720 --> 00:09:52.710
One was medicine
and one was art.

00:09:52.710 --> 00:09:57.760
I decided medicine, my
parents would approve of.

00:09:57.760 --> 00:09:59.570
Art, no.

00:09:59.570 --> 00:10:02.880
So I took a job
first as an orderly.

00:10:02.880 --> 00:10:06.370
I helped with the autopsies
and stuff like that.

00:10:06.370 --> 00:10:09.090
And then I had a
bad car accident.

00:10:09.090 --> 00:10:12.210
I drove a car over a bridge.

00:10:12.210 --> 00:10:13.860
That took a little
while to get over.

00:10:13.860 --> 00:10:20.890
And I reconsidered what were the
most important things in what

00:10:20.890 --> 00:10:24.770
order and what would
give me the best

00:10:24.770 --> 00:10:28.120
feeling of having done
something with my life

00:10:28.120 --> 00:10:29.450
that I wanted to do.

00:10:29.450 --> 00:10:31.580
So I said, well, I really
always have loved art.

00:10:31.580 --> 00:10:35.240
So I spent several years
doing art after that.

00:10:35.240 --> 00:10:38.014
I ran into a professor who
was teaching Baroque art.

00:10:38.014 --> 00:10:39.430
He said, well,
have you ever heard

00:10:39.430 --> 00:10:41.490
of this profession
of conservation?

00:10:41.490 --> 00:10:43.930
They seem to combine
art and science.

00:10:43.930 --> 00:10:46.720
I said, well, I
better look into that.

00:10:46.720 --> 00:10:50.070
So I went to New York and
talked to several people there.

00:10:50.070 --> 00:10:53.494
And then I ended up doing that.

00:10:53.494 --> 00:10:55.160
KISURA HENDRIX: You
have been told to us

00:10:55.160 --> 00:10:57.720
as being one of the
best conservation

00:10:57.720 --> 00:11:00.711
people in the country,
if not the best.

00:11:00.711 --> 00:11:03.150
ANDREW LINS: [INAUDIBLE]
I'm going to get

00:11:03.150 --> 00:11:04.365
into a lot of trouble now.

00:11:04.365 --> 00:11:05.990
KISURA HENDRIX: I
mean, I'm just saying

00:11:05.990 --> 00:11:10.500
that coming from you wanting to
go into the medical profession

00:11:10.500 --> 00:11:13.980
to please your parents to
doing this, which is completely

00:11:13.980 --> 00:11:16.600
different, are you glad that
you went down the path that you

00:11:16.600 --> 00:11:19.600
did instead of going
to be a doctor first

00:11:19.600 --> 00:11:20.550
You know what I mean?

