They don't have to
go work every day.

00:22:41.630 --> 00:22:43.186
They don't have
to pay your bills.

00:22:43.186 --> 00:22:44.810
They don't have to
raise your children.

00:22:44.810 --> 00:22:46.268
They don't have to
be the ones that

00:22:46.268 --> 00:22:48.240
are responsible for your
light and your gift.

00:22:48.240 --> 00:22:50.810
So if you decide that you
don't want to do that anymore,

00:22:50.810 --> 00:22:52.685
then tell the people
who said, you know what,

00:22:52.685 --> 00:22:54.350
y'all, some stuff
has happened to me,

00:22:54.350 --> 00:22:55.890
and I don't want to do this.

00:22:55.890 --> 00:22:57.630
And you've got to
be honest enough

00:22:57.630 --> 00:22:59.890
with yourself to understand,
is this something

00:22:59.890 --> 00:23:03.260
I was created to do, or is
this just something I like?

00:23:03.260 --> 00:23:05.150
Is this something I
was created to do,

00:23:05.150 --> 00:23:08.460
or is this something I think
is going to make me look good?

00:23:08.460 --> 00:23:10.660
Because what I see
a lot of people--

00:23:10.660 --> 00:23:12.694
a lot of young people
doing especially--

00:23:12.694 --> 00:23:14.860
is they think that they
were created to do something

00:23:14.860 --> 00:23:16.318
because they ain't
see nothing else

00:23:16.318 --> 00:23:18.040
or they haven't
opened their minds up

00:23:18.040 --> 00:23:19.380
to other opportunities.

00:23:19.380 --> 00:23:22.460
But so often we
confine ourselves

00:23:22.460 --> 00:23:26.670
to this little box of doctor,
lawyer, engineer, teacher,

00:23:26.670 --> 00:23:28.980
business person.

00:23:28.980 --> 00:23:30.500
Free yourself [INAUDIBLE].

00:23:30.500 --> 00:23:31.722
This is my key.

00:23:31.722 --> 00:23:33.180
ABEL HABTEGEORGIS:
I appreciate it.

00:23:33.180 --> 00:23:33.770
[? JEFF JOHNSON: Thank you ?]
[INAUDIBLE].

00:23:33.770 --> 00:23:35.430
ABEL HABTEGEORGIS: The
conversation, the wisdom,

00:23:35.430 --> 00:23:36.096
everything, man.

00:23:36.096 --> 00:23:37.747
[? JEFF JOHNSON: Thank ?] you.

00:23:37.747 --> 00:23:39.330
NATHAN GEBHARD: What
I love about Jeff

00:23:39.330 --> 00:23:42.370
is just the idea that we
put ourselves in the box.

00:23:42.370 --> 00:23:44.550
And as we looked at how
we wanted to round out

00:23:44.550 --> 00:23:47.140
that first section of let go.

00:23:47.140 --> 00:23:49.940
It really ends with this chapter
called "The Blank Canvas".

00:23:49.940 --> 00:23:54.530
And the take there is if we
really accept that noise,

00:23:54.530 --> 00:23:57.270
we're living a life
of paint by numbers.

00:23:57.270 --> 00:24:02.250
And the more we can strip away
and wash those instructions

00:24:02.250 --> 00:24:06.410
manuals away, the more we can
really start from a clean slate

00:24:06.410 --> 00:24:08.290
and really think
about who we are.

00:24:08.290 --> 00:24:11.920
And so that's how we end
that process of let go.

00:24:11.920 --> 00:24:15.190
And that brings us into define.

00:24:15.190 --> 00:24:18.370
I think the thing
about define for us

00:24:18.370 --> 00:24:22.370
is that-- I think before
we started on the road trip

00:24:22.370 --> 00:24:26.430
we had this expectation that
all of these different people

00:24:26.430 --> 00:24:28.990
had always had it figured out.

00:24:28.990 --> 00:24:31.950
So when we sat down with
Howard Schultz from Starbucks,

00:24:31.950 --> 00:24:34.910
we figured he always knew
he was really into coffee

00:24:34.910 --> 00:24:36.824
and he just knew how to do that.

00:24:36.824 --> 00:24:39.240
When we sat down with David
Neeleman, who started JetBlue,

00:24:39.240 --> 00:24:41.480
we just figured that guy,
he's all about planes,

00:24:41.480 --> 00:24:43.710
straight line to success.

00:24:43.710 --> 00:24:45.377
Wanda Sykes, same thing.

00:24:45.377 --> 00:24:47.460
She probably was the
funniest person in her class,

00:24:47.460 --> 00:24:49.140
always had confidence
up on stage,

00:24:49.140 --> 00:24:51.710
and she killed it every time.

00:24:51.710 --> 00:24:53.872
After those
interviews, we realized

00:24:53.872 --> 00:24:55.830
that Howard Schultz was
the first in his family

00:24:55.830 --> 00:24:56.990
to go to college.

00:24:56.990 --> 00:24:59.580
And in college he was so
poor he was donating blood

00:24:59.580 --> 00:25:01.570
to have enough money to eat.

00:25:01.570 --> 00:25:05.490
You hear David Neeleman talk
about being an executive vice

00:25:05.490 --> 00:25:08.145
president at Southwest
Airlines and then being fired

00:25:08.145 --> 00:25:10.160
and how devastating
that was for him and how

00:25:10.160 --> 00:25:13.620
he had to rebuild his sense
of self and his identity

00:25:13.620 --> 00:25:16.060
and what he wanted
to create, which

00:25:16.060 --> 00:25:18.160
ultimately resulted in JetBlue.

00:25:18.160 --> 00:25:20.640
And we learned that
Wanda Sykes for years

00:25:20.640 --> 00:25:22.460
was working at the NSA.

00:25:22.460 --> 00:25:25.120
That was her way
of paying the bills

00:25:25.120 --> 00:25:27.020
while she gained this
confidence, while she

00:25:27.020 --> 00:25:28.820
became a comedian.

00:25:28.820 --> 00:25:32.510
And so it was a really
eye-opening piece to us

00:25:32.510 --> 00:25:35.980
to think that people didn't
just become instantly.

00:25:35.980 --> 00:25:37.670
They moved in incremental steps.

00:25:37.670 --> 00:25:42.900
And I think a great example
of that is this guy.

00:25:42.900 --> 00:25:45.410
He is one of my favorite
interviews of recent.

00:25:45.410 --> 00:25:48.060
His name's Adam Steltzner.

00:25:48.060 --> 00:25:51.900
When Adam was first
looking around,

00:25:51.900 --> 00:25:54.880
the only thing he knew he was
interested in was nothing.

00:25:54.880 --> 00:25:56.430
He had no driver.

00:25:56.430 --> 00:26:00.330
He was not particularly
compelled by anything.

00:26:00.330 --> 00:26:04.280
He would start things
and then back off them.

00:26:04.280 --> 00:26:06.970
He isn't sure if he
graduated from high school.

00:26:06.970 --> 00:26:09.300
He was one grade
away and decided,

00:26:09.300 --> 00:26:11.910
I just won't go back and check
those transcripts to see.

00:26:11.910 --> 00:26:14.480
And at the point of his
story really starting,

00:26:14.480 --> 00:26:16.740
he said, I was
playing in a band.

00:26:16.740 --> 00:26:20.570
And every night I was driving
home over the Bay Bridge,

00:26:20.570 --> 00:26:23.890
and I noticed that the
stars moved in the sky.

00:26:23.890 --> 00:26:28.280
And he says this in an
admission of ignorance and irony

00:26:28.280 --> 00:26:31.922
that he had no idea that
the stars moved in the sky,

00:26:31.922 --> 00:26:33.880
that the moon is in a
different place each day,

00:26:33.880 --> 00:26:39.130
that Orion is not here, but
it's there the next month.

00:26:39.130 --> 00:26:41.500
And so on that simple little,
why do the stars move,

00:26:41.500 --> 00:26:43.480
he decided to go to
an astronomy class

00:26:43.480 --> 00:26:46.822
at a local junior
college, and just say,

00:26:46.822 --> 00:26:48.030
I'm going to figure this out.

00:26:48.030 --> 00:26:49.220
Why?

00:26:49.220 --> 00:26:51.770
And it just bit.

00:26:51.770 --> 00:26:54.480
That was an interest--
this idea about space

00:26:54.480 --> 00:26:56.330
and how these things
come together,

00:26:56.330 --> 00:27:01.290
how formulas can really governed
the rules of how things move,

00:27:01.290 --> 00:27:02.910
both in space and on earth.

00:27:02.910 --> 00:27:04.700
And he just started
to follow that.

00:27:04.700 --> 00:27:07.980
And that was a drip, and then
the next degree was a drip.

00:27:07.980 --> 00:27:10.460
And he all a sudden
finds himself enraptured

00:27:10.460 --> 00:27:13.160
by this interest of the stars.

00:27:13.160 --> 00:27:15.390
He lands a job at JPL.

00:27:15.390 --> 00:27:18.805
And he starts
engineering landings.

00:27:21.430 --> 00:27:23.930
He became the go-to guy
for complex problems

00:27:23.930 --> 00:27:26.320
about how to land
things in space.

00:27:26.320 --> 00:27:29.790
And to start from the guy that
didn't know the stars moved,

00:27:29.790 --> 00:27:33.980
he ultimately was the one
that engineered the landing

00:27:33.980 --> 00:27:37.260
or led the landing on
the Mars Curiosity Rover.

00:27:37.260 --> 00:27:41.030
So when you saw that-- what
was it-- they called it,

00:27:41.030 --> 00:27:44.020
I think, seven minutes of
terror, that was his team

00:27:44.020 --> 00:27:45.400
putting that together.

00:27:45.400 --> 00:27:49.220
And he's ultimately responsible,
him and the team at JPL,

00:27:49.220 --> 00:27:50.760
for landing that rover.

00:27:50.760 --> 00:27:53.760
And it just was such an
empowering piece for us

00:27:53.760 --> 00:27:57.140
to realize people didn't
always have it figured out.

00:27:57.140 --> 00:27:58.890
And I think that his
story is so much more

00:27:58.890 --> 00:28:02.974
consistent than the very few
minority of the individuals

00:28:02.974 --> 00:28:04.640
that we met with that
said, oh, I always

00:28:04.640 --> 00:28:07.360
knew I wanted to be a writer
and I just became a writer.

00:28:07.360 --> 00:28:11.870
That is the almost 0%.

00:28:11.870 --> 00:28:15.570
And I think that really ties
into this idea of career.

00:28:15.570 --> 00:28:17.190
From our perspective,
from all these

00:28:17.190 --> 00:28:19.860
1,000 plus interviews,
what we really see

00:28:19.860 --> 00:28:22.690
is that our current way in
which we approach career

00:28:22.690 --> 00:28:26.160
is like taking binoculars
and looking at it backwards.

00:28:26.160 --> 00:28:29.200
If we look at that experience
of going to the career center,

00:28:29.200 --> 00:28:31.260
more often than
not it's this idea

00:28:31.260 --> 00:28:34.280
that you just pick an
occupation in the future

00:28:34.280 --> 00:28:36.540
and then reverse
engineer backwards.

00:28:36.540 --> 00:28:38.580
If you're in a career,
it's pick the next career

00:28:38.580 --> 00:28:40.577
and then reverse
engineer backwards.

00:28:40.577 --> 00:28:41.410
What are the skills?

00:28:41.410 --> 00:28:43.490
What are the
degrees that I need?

00:28:43.490 --> 00:28:46.590
But what we saw was the
total different approach.

00:28:46.590 --> 00:28:48.720
The people that really
found themselves happy

00:28:48.720 --> 00:28:50.960
and engaged in the work
that they were doing,

00:28:50.960 --> 00:28:52.230
they followed a simple thing.

00:28:52.230 --> 00:28:55.620
And it was just a
simple piece, which is

00:28:55.620 --> 00:28:57.450
they followed their interests.

00:28:57.450 --> 00:28:58.460
This is Richard Meier.

00:28:58.460 --> 00:29:00.681
He was the architect
for the Getty Museum.

00:29:00.681 --> 00:29:02.180
And he said, "When
I was growing up,

00:29:02.180 --> 00:29:05.280
my parents had a
basement in their house,

00:29:05.280 --> 00:29:08.410
and I had a drafting board where
I would make drawings and model

00:29:08.410 --> 00:29:10.740
boats and paper airplanes.

00:29:10.740 --> 00:29:13.520
I just liked making things."

00:29:13.520 --> 00:29:16.536
He didn't say, I want
to be an architect.

00:29:16.536 --> 00:29:18.160
I think for the most
part, when we say,

00:29:18.160 --> 00:29:19.770
I'm going to be a
consultant, it's

00:29:19.770 --> 00:29:23.460
to end that awkward conversation
at the family barbecue.

00:29:23.460 --> 00:29:26.900
What we saw was
people really gaining

00:29:26.900 --> 00:29:29.222
their own sense of identity
was when they just said,

00:29:29.222 --> 00:29:31.180
I have this interest and
I'm going to pursue it

00:29:31.180 --> 00:29:33.900
and I'm going to
see where it goes.

00:29:33.900 --> 00:29:35.520
And so if there
was one core piece

00:29:35.520 --> 00:29:37.770
that I would say that is
about "Roadtrip Nation," that

00:29:37.770 --> 00:29:41.210
is about this book, it is
pursue your interests, not

00:29:41.210 --> 00:29:42.450
an occupation.

00:29:42.450 --> 00:29:44.640
And we have seen that
time and time again.

00:29:47.380 --> 00:29:49.950
When we started to think
about pursuing the interests,

00:29:49.950 --> 00:29:54.470
we also looked at how
to put that together.

00:29:54.470 --> 00:29:56.769
And what we saw was this
idea of this framework

00:29:56.769 --> 00:29:57.560
called the roadmap.

00:29:57.560 --> 00:30:00.120
And that's ultimately what
we named the book after.

00:30:00.120 --> 00:30:02.420
It's this idea that
you're mashing together

00:30:02.420 --> 00:30:03.430
multiple interests.

00:30:03.430 --> 00:30:06.290
Because when we
went to JDK Design,

00:30:06.290 --> 00:30:08.210
we weren't just
interviewing a designer.

00:30:08.210 --> 00:30:09.585
We were interviewing
the designer

00:30:09.585 --> 00:30:11.700
that puts art on snowboards.

00:30:11.700 --> 00:30:14.780
When we went and
saw Adam Steltzner

00:30:14.780 --> 00:30:17.060
it's not just science
or engineering.

00:30:17.060 --> 00:30:19.480
It's those combined
together with space.

00:30:19.480 --> 00:30:23.640
It's all these people combining
multiple things together.

00:30:23.640 --> 00:30:26.360
And what we started to look
at was more often than not,

00:30:26.360 --> 00:30:27.710
there was something deeper.

00:30:27.710 --> 00:30:30.400
There was this thing which
we refer to as a foundation.

00:30:30.400 --> 00:30:33.400
So for me, like Richard
Meier, it really

00:30:33.400 --> 00:30:34.650
doesn't matter what I'm doing.

00:30:34.650 --> 00:30:37.090
I will be lit up
with almost anything

00:30:37.090 --> 00:30:40.444
as long as I'm making things, as
long as I'm building something.

00:30:40.444 --> 00:30:42.860
The interests that I have--
design and technology-- that's

00:30:42.860 --> 00:30:44.360
the way I manifest it.

00:30:44.360 --> 00:30:46.330
But making things,
whether it's LEGOs

00:30:46.330 --> 00:30:50.279
with my daughter, a website,
a boat, anything, that's

00:30:50.279 --> 00:30:51.320
really what lights me up.

00:30:51.320 --> 00:30:53.660
And so we saw time
and time people

00:30:53.660 --> 00:30:55.965
were finding their
own foundation

00:30:55.965 --> 00:30:58.540
and then combining
multiple interests.

00:30:58.540 --> 00:31:01.430
And so this is a really good
example of an interview--

00:31:01.430 --> 00:31:05.220
just up the road-- from Anna.

00:31:05.220 --> 00:31:07.240
ANNA HORJILLOSA: I
went to UC Berkeley.

00:31:07.240 --> 00:31:09.660
And I started out as a
philosophy major and an art

00:31:09.660 --> 00:31:10.350
major.

00:31:10.350 --> 00:31:12.670
And then I took anthropology.

00:31:12.670 --> 00:31:16.510
And then I thought, you know,
I'm going to do theater.

00:31:16.510 --> 00:31:18.810
And after I got out,
I was like, I'm just

00:31:18.810 --> 00:31:21.380
going to try to get a real job.

00:31:21.380 --> 00:31:24.280
But I wanted to be in a
place that felt right.

00:31:24.280 --> 00:31:26.510
And I applied to the
Asian Art Museum.

00:31:26.510 --> 00:31:29.905
I applied for the program
assistant position

00:31:29.905 --> 00:31:31.930
in performing arts.

00:31:31.930 --> 00:31:37.290
And I have museum experience,
I had my anthro background,

00:31:37.290 --> 00:31:37.980
I had theater.

00:31:37.980 --> 00:31:39.820
It just came together.

00:31:39.820 --> 00:31:41.670
And it was totally unplanned.

00:31:41.670 --> 00:31:45.820
The thing is I never knew a job
like what I have now existed

00:31:45.820 --> 00:31:47.160
or could exist.

00:31:47.160 --> 00:31:50.870
I just sort of positioned
myself with things

00:31:50.870 --> 00:31:54.260
that really felt right.

00:31:54.260 --> 00:31:57.180
It's really a matter of
instinct on some level

00:31:57.180 --> 00:32:00.040
and a broad plotting of things.

00:32:00.040 --> 00:32:02.084
Your path is what
you make of it.

00:32:02.084 --> 00:32:04.500
There are positions out there,
there are careers out there

00:32:04.500 --> 00:32:08.050
that you can fit into,
but there are also things

00:32:08.050 --> 00:32:10.280
that you can make yourself.

00:32:10.280 --> 00:32:14.280
And you have to just trust
that you have something

00:32:14.280 --> 00:32:18.674
unique to offer and to
be consistent with that

00:32:18.674 --> 00:32:19.340
in your choices.

00:32:22.699 --> 00:32:24.990
NATHAN GEBHARD: And what I
really love about her is she

00:32:24.990 --> 00:32:26.760
is mashing these pieces up.

00:32:26.760 --> 00:32:29.200
She's mashing up
anthropology, theater,

00:32:29.200 --> 00:32:31.069
and in the context of a museum.

00:32:31.069 --> 00:32:33.110
And to give you guys some
more examples of people

00:32:33.110 --> 00:32:35.250
we've interviewed,
this is Peter Travers.

00:32:35.250 --> 00:32:37.510
He's a film critic at
"Rolling Stone Magazine."

00:32:37.510 --> 00:32:40.060
He's all about sharing stories
with film and journalism.

00:32:40.060 --> 00:32:41.810
And you could probably
add in music there,

00:32:41.810 --> 00:32:44.190
if you wanted, from
"Rolling Stone."

00:32:44.190 --> 00:32:45.380
We've got Jessica Matthews.

00:32:45.380 --> 00:32:47.782
She's CEO of Uncharted Play.

00:32:47.782 --> 00:32:50.115
She's all about helping people
in sports and technology.

00:32:50.115 --> 00:32:51.170
You might have seen her.

00:32:51.170 --> 00:32:54.350
She was one of the engineers
of this soccer ball

00:32:54.350 --> 00:32:57.590
that small rural communities
in Africa could play with.

00:32:57.590 --> 00:32:59.950
And during the day,
while they're kicking it,

00:32:59.950 --> 00:33:04.280
through the motion generated of
movement, it's storing energy.

00:33:04.280 --> 00:33:07.810
And they can then plug an actual
light into that soccer ball

00:33:07.810 --> 00:33:10.580
and use it as light in
their homes in the evening.

00:33:10.580 --> 00:33:11.690
It's an amazing story.

00:33:11.690 --> 00:33:13.805
And she is combining
science into sports

00:33:13.805 --> 00:33:15.055
and helping people altogether.

00:33:17.632 --> 00:33:19.840
If you look at Jehmu Greene,
when we interviewed her,

00:33:19.840 --> 00:33:21.980
she was the president
of Rock the Vote.

00:33:21.980 --> 00:33:24.060
She [INAUDIBLE] that
she believes in,

00:33:24.060 --> 00:33:25.950
but she's not doing
that in the abstract.

00:33:25.950 --> 00:33:27.640
She's doing it in
music and politics.

00:33:30.250 --> 00:33:32.210
And when we sat down
with Ariel Helwani,

00:33:32.210 --> 00:33:35.490
he was all about
accomplishing goals.

00:33:35.490 --> 00:33:39.390
This was a guy who really
had this goal of getting

00:33:39.390 --> 00:33:44.310
into MMA reporting, but
he was deathly afraid

00:33:44.310 --> 00:33:45.410
of the limelight.

00:33:45.410 --> 00:33:48.750
He was petrified
of other people.

00:33:48.750 --> 00:33:51.030
When he was in college,
he lived in the dorms,

00:33:51.030 --> 00:33:53.950
and he literally would wait
till 2:00 in the morning

00:33:53.950 --> 00:33:55.350
to go brush his teeth.

00:33:55.350 --> 00:33:58.710
He was that afraid of
people, but his goal

00:33:58.710 --> 00:34:00.290
was to be a reporter for MMA.

00:34:00.290 --> 00:34:04.690
I have no idea why he chose that
goal, but that was his thing.

00:34:04.690 --> 00:34:05.760
And he started small.

00:34:05.760 --> 00:34:07.820
He started in a
local radio station

00:34:07.820 --> 00:34:10.190
where he could just put his
headphones on and his hoodie

00:34:10.190 --> 00:34:11.580
and talk into the mic.

00:34:11.580 --> 00:34:14.090
Then he started a
blog, added some video

00:34:14.090 --> 00:34:16.670
to that blog of doing
interviews with fighters,

00:34:16.670 --> 00:34:20.270
and all of sudden,
he is the guy at AOL.

00:34:20.270 --> 00:34:25.429
He's one of the key
people in the MMA space.

00:34:25.429 --> 00:34:27.429
Now I wanted to just take
a little bit more time

00:34:27.429 --> 00:34:30.060
to tell you a story that
really articulates, I think,

00:34:30.060 --> 00:34:33.010
a lot of what we've talked about
before in terms of shedding

00:34:33.010 --> 00:34:36.330
the noise, in terms of evolving
this idea of drip, drip,

00:34:36.330 --> 00:34:38.659
splash, and then
mashing up of interests.

00:34:38.659 --> 00:34:40.070
So this is Jimmy Chin.

00:34:40.070 --> 00:34:40.739
He's a skier.

00:34:40.739 --> 00:34:43.100
He's a rock climber.

00:34:43.100 --> 00:34:44.790
He's an adventurer.

00:34:44.790 --> 00:34:48.189
He's a North Face athlete.

00:34:48.189 --> 00:34:49.980
Probably a month before
we interviewed him,

00:34:49.980 --> 00:34:53.560
he had just shot the photo
of the cover of "National

00:34:53.560 --> 00:34:55.659
Geographic" with Alex
[? Hahn ?] just standing

00:34:55.659 --> 00:34:56.949
on the ledge with no ropes.

00:34:56.949 --> 00:35:00.030
So that was Jimmy Chin's photo.

00:35:00.030 --> 00:35:02.710
But he came from a very
traditional family.

00:35:02.710 --> 00:35:07.210
His parents were very
much focused on education.

00:35:07.210 --> 00:35:11.370
And he did a lot of
things to make them happy.

00:35:11.370 --> 00:35:14.270
He was an accomplished
violin player.

00:35:14.270 --> 00:35:16.069
He really pursued
college in a place

00:35:16.069 --> 00:35:17.860
where it wasn't maybe
necessarily the thing

00:35:17.860 --> 00:35:19.550
that he would have chosen.

00:35:19.550 --> 00:35:21.430
But he did these things
to make them happy.

00:35:21.430 --> 00:35:25.060
And he said that the one thing
he chose for himself to do

00:35:25.060 --> 00:35:26.730
was rock climbing.

00:35:26.730 --> 00:35:30.150
And so he said after
college to his parents,

00:35:30.150 --> 00:35:31.290
just give me one year.

00:35:31.290 --> 00:35:34.980
I'm just going to climb for one
year, ski for one year, and see

00:35:34.980 --> 00:35:37.262
what happens, and then
I'll go get that job.

00:35:37.262 --> 00:35:38.095
I'll be that lawyer.

00:35:38.095 --> 00:35:40.178
He literally thought that
there was three options,

00:35:40.178 --> 00:35:44.080
just be a doctor or be a
lawyer or be a business person.

00:35:44.080 --> 00:35:47.090
And I think all of those are
totally admirable occupations.

00:35:47.090 --> 00:35:49.270
They just weren't
right for Jimmy.

00:35:49.270 --> 00:35:53.360
So he said, just give me
time to live my piece first.

00:35:53.360 --> 00:35:54.290
So he started.

00:35:54.290 --> 00:35:58.572
And he started at literally
just this simply rock climbing.

00:35:58.572 --> 00:36:00.880
And that interest grew.

00:36:00.880 --> 00:36:04.010
And he was getting more and more
accomplished in rock climbing.

00:36:04.010 --> 00:36:07.630
And then one day on a
climb, one of his buddies

00:36:07.630 --> 00:36:09.770
was trying to learn
to take photographs

00:36:09.770 --> 00:36:12.210
and wanted to start a business
of taking photographs.

00:36:12.210 --> 00:36:13.810
And they were on this pitch.

00:36:13.810 --> 00:36:16.500
And his buddy couldn't quite
get the angle that he wanted.

00:36:16.500 --> 00:36:18.583
So he handed the camera
to Jimmy and he said, hey,

00:36:18.583 --> 00:36:19.970
will you just take this photo?

00:36:19.970 --> 00:36:22.871
Whatever you can,
just take a photo.

00:36:22.871 --> 00:36:23.370
Whatever.

00:36:23.370 --> 00:36:25.870
A couple of weeks went by, and
that friend came back to him.

00:36:25.870 --> 00:36:28.465
And he was like, yeah,
yeah, I sold a photo.

00:36:28.465 --> 00:36:30.120
It was your photo.

00:36:30.120 --> 00:36:32.770
The only photo this
guy sold was the photo

00:36:32.770 --> 00:36:34.420
that Jimmy took on that camera.

00:36:34.420 --> 00:36:37.390
And at the time, Jimmy
was living in his car.

00:36:37.390 --> 00:36:39.330
He was rock climbing.

00:36:39.330 --> 00:36:41.400
And he got $500 for that photo.

00:36:41.400 --> 00:36:44.780
And he just sat there and
he said, if all I need to do

00:36:44.780 --> 00:36:48.890
is sell 12 photos and I can
live for the entire year.

00:36:48.890 --> 00:36:51.499
And he just kept going.

00:36:51.499 --> 00:36:53.290
It was just this pursuing
of this interest.

00:36:53.290 --> 00:36:57.750
He lived in that
car for six years,

00:36:57.750 --> 00:37:00.610
but his skills and his
interests were evolving.

00:37:00.610 --> 00:37:02.820
It went from rock
climbing to high Himalayan

00:37:02.820 --> 00:37:06.570
climbing to these really
extensive expeditions.

00:37:06.570 --> 00:37:11.200
And then it even went further
to leading really complex

00:37:11.200 --> 00:37:13.420
expeditions in remote locations.

00:37:13.420 --> 00:37:15.340
And what's interesting
about Jimmy's story

00:37:15.340 --> 00:37:17.260
at this point was
he said, you know,

00:37:17.260 --> 00:37:19.170
I couldn't have led
these expeditions

00:37:19.170 --> 00:37:22.045
without that education that I
had, without these experiences

00:37:22.045 --> 00:37:24.720
that I've had before,
because people didn't need--

00:37:24.720 --> 00:37:27.940
when they're going to go climb
a crazy peak-- you couldn't

00:37:27.940 --> 00:37:30.300
get a team that said, OK,
I need one photographer.

00:37:30.300 --> 00:37:32.680
I need one videographer,
one climber,

00:37:32.680 --> 00:37:34.390
and then one operations guy.

00:37:34.390 --> 00:37:37.050
You need somebody that brings
all of those things together.

00:37:37.050 --> 00:37:39.004
And Jimmy, through
his experience,

00:37:39.004 --> 00:37:40.670
through that pursuing
of these interests

00:37:40.670 --> 00:37:44.140
and this step by step approach,
really created this place

00:37:44.140 --> 00:37:46.520
where he was one of the
few people that could

00:37:46.520 --> 00:37:48.035
take on some of these things.

00:37:48.035 --> 00:37:52.280
And when I asked him what advice
would you have to people trying

00:37:52.280 --> 00:37:54.830
to define their own road,
he simply used this climbing

00:37:54.830 --> 00:37:57.500
reference, which I think
really applies, which is,

00:37:57.500 --> 00:37:59.460
[? "Commit ?] and
figure it out."

00:37:59.460 --> 00:38:01.320
He committed to rock climbing.

00:38:01.320 --> 00:38:02.950
That evolved to photography.

00:38:02.950 --> 00:38:04.812
That evolved to leading
these expeditions.

00:38:04.812 --> 00:38:08.330
That evolved to videography, to
starting a production company.

00:38:08.330 --> 00:38:11.909
And if you have any interest on
Instagram, check out his feed.

00:38:11.909 --> 00:38:12.825
It's really inspiring.

00:38:15.650 --> 00:38:18.840
So at this point, just
reflect on your own roadmap.

00:38:18.840 --> 00:38:24.010
Imagine what are the interests
that you would smash together.

00:38:24.010 --> 00:38:27.500
If noise was nonexistent, if
you really had that freedom,

00:38:27.500 --> 00:38:31.870
what would be that thing
that you would take?

00:38:31.870 --> 00:38:33.532
And this gets us into
the become piece,

00:38:33.532 --> 00:38:34.740
the last section of the book.

00:38:38.372 --> 00:38:40.080
As we started putting
this book together,

00:38:40.080 --> 00:38:43.915
I think the worst advice that
I think I've ever received

00:38:43.915 --> 00:38:47.150
and I could give to anybody
would be follow your passions.

00:38:47.150 --> 00:38:50.937
Because I think there's
a huge problem with that.

00:38:50.937 --> 00:38:53.020
It makes it sound like you
should know it already.

00:38:53.020 --> 00:38:55.740
It makes you sound like this
thing is so big that you've

00:38:55.740 --> 00:38:56.640
only got one passion.

00:38:56.640 --> 00:38:59.880
It's like find that right
one partner in this world,

00:38:59.880 --> 00:39:01.390
the perfect match.

00:39:01.390 --> 00:39:03.280
And what we saw
was people did not

00:39:03.280 --> 00:39:05.660
approach their life that way.

00:39:05.660 --> 00:39:07.410
They dipped their
toe in the water.

00:39:07.410 --> 00:39:10.140
A woman that we interviewed
over here at Google,

00:39:10.140 --> 00:39:14.270
she said, you're looking at
me now in this occupation

00:39:14.270 --> 00:39:17.230
and in the success that
I have, and you think,

00:39:17.230 --> 00:39:20.420
I'm doing so well, but you
didn't see all the steps

00:39:20.420 --> 00:39:21.110
that I got here.

00:39:21.110 --> 00:39:22.500
And her analogy was beautiful.

00:39:22.500 --> 00:39:24.430
She said, it's like
you're looking at somebody

00:39:24.430 --> 00:39:26.330
who's swimming in cold ocean.

00:39:26.330 --> 00:39:27.920
They didn't just run
in there and jump

00:39:27.920 --> 00:39:29.472
and say, oh, this is great.

00:39:29.472 --> 00:39:30.680
She's like, I ran down there.

00:39:30.680 --> 00:39:31.610
I put my toe in the water.

00:39:31.610 --> 00:39:32.276
It was freezing.

00:39:32.276 --> 00:39:33.575
I backed off.

00:39:33.575 --> 00:39:34.200
I ran in there.

00:39:34.200 --> 00:39:35.158
I got down to my knees.

00:39:35.158 --> 00:39:36.070
It was too cold.

00:39:36.070 --> 00:39:36.810
I failed again.

00:39:36.810 --> 00:39:37.980
I ran back off.

00:39:37.980 --> 00:39:40.630
And eventually she gets to the
place where she's neck deep

00:39:40.630 --> 00:39:42.140
and then she's swimming.

00:39:42.140 --> 00:39:45.390
But we connect to these dots
that really aren't there.

00:39:45.390 --> 00:39:49.420
And so this idea that you should
follow your passion-- passion's

00:39:49.420 --> 00:39:51.480
the destination if
you do it all right,

00:39:51.480 --> 00:39:53.910
but it's not an approach.

00:39:53.910 --> 00:39:56.670
It's really following
your interests

00:39:56.670 --> 00:39:58.990
and exploring that passion
and finding validation

00:39:58.990 --> 00:40:01.480
where your interests
meet your skills.

00:40:01.480 --> 00:40:03.630
Then you arrive at
that place of passion.

00:40:03.630 --> 00:40:07.640
But it's just not a reasonable
bit of advice to give anybody.

00:40:07.640 --> 00:40:09.870
And we have not seen
that come into play

00:40:09.870 --> 00:40:12.200
with the people we interviewed.

00:40:12.200 --> 00:40:17.527
I think the most apt
example of these baby steps

00:40:17.527 --> 00:40:19.110
is this interview
that we had with Jad

00:40:19.110 --> 00:40:24.085
Abumrad, the co-founder
and host of "RadioLab."

00:40:24.085 --> 00:40:26.110
And he has this
great analogy that he

00:40:26.110 --> 00:40:29.667
pulls called the adjacent
possible from science.

00:40:29.667 --> 00:40:30.750
So we'll just tap into it.

00:40:30.750 --> 00:40:31.840
ZACHARIAH COWAN: One
thing that comes up

00:40:31.840 --> 00:40:33.610
a lot is we're
about about defining

00:40:33.610 --> 00:40:36.160
our own roads as opposed to not
taking somebody else's road.

00:40:36.160 --> 00:40:40.120
But how did you take it
to that next level of,

00:40:40.120 --> 00:40:42.920
you need to be more open
to other options and things

00:40:42.920 --> 00:40:45.530
like that.

00:40:45.530 --> 00:40:48.410
JAD ABUMRAD: Let me get
abstract for a second.

00:40:48.410 --> 00:40:50.035
I'm going to bring
in some highfalutin,

00:40:50.035 --> 00:40:53.690
and you can tell
me to be concrete.

00:40:53.690 --> 00:40:56.720
But there's this
theory in evolution

00:40:56.720 --> 00:40:58.870
called the adjacent
possible, which

00:40:58.870 --> 00:41:02.290
is that if you imagine
the primordial soup is

00:41:02.290 --> 00:41:05.200
full of all these chemicals.

00:41:05.200 --> 00:41:06.200
Arsenic was in there.

00:41:06.200 --> 00:41:07.724
There's amino acids
floating around.

00:41:07.724 --> 00:41:10.140
Those things aren't going to
suddenly bump into each other

00:41:10.140 --> 00:41:14.110
and create a human
being, or even a flower.

00:41:14.110 --> 00:41:16.950
So it's not part of the
possibility of that space

00:41:16.950 --> 00:41:18.910
to create the flower.

00:41:18.910 --> 00:41:21.550
But you can take an amino acid
and you can take a fat cell.

00:41:21.550 --> 00:41:22.980
You can slam them together.

00:41:22.980 --> 00:41:25.770
Suddenly you've got a cell
and suddenly that cell

00:41:25.770 --> 00:41:28.310
has more possibilities--
a two-celled organism.

00:41:28.310 --> 00:41:32.225
And eventually an amoeba or
something-- I don't know.

00:41:32.225 --> 00:41:33.600
So you have to
ask yourself, what

00:41:33.600 --> 00:41:36.050
is your adjacent
possible, in some sense.

00:41:36.050 --> 00:41:40.060
Right now you're, in a way,
in your own primordial soup

00:41:40.060 --> 00:41:44.480
of dreams, but you have to
think of your possibilities

00:41:44.480 --> 00:41:49.350
in both the most expansive and
the most constrained-- like,

00:41:49.350 --> 00:41:52.170
OK, you know, I can't
be Michael Jordan

00:41:52.170 --> 00:41:55.130
but maybe I could go
play in a pickup game

00:41:55.130 --> 00:41:57.450
and work on my jump shot,
something like that.

00:41:57.450 --> 00:41:59.741
There's a way in which you
always have to ask yourself,

00:41:59.741 --> 00:42:03.509
what is possible right
outside my border?

00:42:03.509 --> 00:42:05.550
NATHAN GEBHARD: I think
that piece of possibility

00:42:05.550 --> 00:42:08.920
is very in line with
everything that we've

00:42:08.920 --> 00:42:11.302
experienced with "Roadtrip."

00:42:11.302 --> 00:42:14.070
We had no idea how to film.

00:42:14.070 --> 00:42:17.240
We had no idea how
to write a book.

00:42:17.240 --> 00:42:19.450
But we figured there was
some baby steps that we

00:42:19.450 --> 00:42:20.720
could take along the way.

00:42:23.520 --> 00:42:26.594
The other piece that I love is
this quote by Veronica Belmont.

00:42:26.594 --> 00:42:28.760
She says, "If you're really
passionate about a topic

00:42:28.760 --> 00:42:30.218
and you want to
work in that field,

00:42:30.218 --> 00:42:32.450
you should already be doing it."

00:42:32.450 --> 00:42:35.960
And I think that that
translates and is

00:42:35.960 --> 00:42:38.140
a main piece for the
chapter in the book

00:42:38.140 --> 00:42:41.440
called Practice Shmactice--
the idea that-- what

00:42:41.440 --> 00:42:44.736
your coaches would always say
is-- practice makes perfect.

00:42:44.736 --> 00:42:47.110
And I think we would really
say that from our experience,

00:42:47.110 --> 00:42:49.090
doing makes perfect.

00:42:49.090 --> 00:42:51.110
There probably is no
such thing as perfect.

00:42:51.110 --> 00:42:53.360
But it's the actual
act of doing.

00:42:53.360 --> 00:42:54.890
If you want to be
an actor, you're

00:42:54.890 --> 00:42:57.120
an actor the second you
turn that camera on yourself

00:42:57.120 --> 00:42:58.030
and start acting.

00:42:58.030 --> 00:42:59.785
If you want to be
a writer, you're

00:42:59.785 --> 00:43:02.010
a writer the second
you start a blog.

00:43:02.010 --> 00:43:04.530
If you're into editing,
start that now.

00:43:04.530 --> 00:43:06.120
I think the world
has changed in a way

00:43:06.120 --> 00:43:09.100
that the avenues to get
into something that you're

00:43:09.100 --> 00:43:11.280
interested are right
in front of us.

00:43:11.280 --> 00:43:13.480
We could open a store
on Etsy for free.

00:43:13.480 --> 00:43:15.260
We can do all of these
different things.

00:43:15.260 --> 00:43:18.790
There are many different ways
to engage in your interest.

00:43:18.790 --> 00:43:21.760
And her point, I think,
is just so poignant

00:43:21.760 --> 00:43:23.670
because we should
already be doing it.

00:43:23.670 --> 00:43:26.035
We should already be
using every decision

00:43:26.035 --> 00:43:29.855
that we make in tying that into
the interests that we have.

00:43:32.830 --> 00:43:37.990
The other piece-- as we think
about becoming, is failure.

00:43:37.990 --> 00:43:40.900
And this is a guy that we
interviewed, Craig Brewer.

00:43:40.900 --> 00:43:43.350
He wrote a film called
"Hustle &amp; Flow."

00:43:43.350 --> 00:43:48.480
And the song in "Hustle &amp; Flow"
was nominated for an Oscar.

00:43:48.480 --> 00:43:52.430
And he was an amazing guy who
told us this story about a film

00:43:52.430 --> 00:43:55.940
that he had shot,
spent $40,000 on,

00:43:55.940 --> 00:43:59.350
and never-- it was
so bad he didn't even

00:43:59.350 --> 00:44:02.662
pay to have it developed.

00:44:02.662 --> 00:44:04.630
Can you imagine spending
$40,000 on something

00:44:04.630 --> 00:44:07.660
and then just saying it's so
bad I can't go any further?

00:44:07.660 --> 00:44:11.410
So this is somebody that was
really experienced in failure.

00:44:11.410 --> 00:44:13.400
And if you ever see the
film "Hustle &amp; Flow,"

00:44:13.400 --> 00:44:15.710
it very much ties into
his own personal story

00:44:15.710 --> 00:44:17.945
in a very dynamic way.

00:44:17.945 --> 00:44:19.570
But he talked about
getting to failure.

00:44:19.570 --> 00:44:22.465
And I think that
the idea of failure

00:44:22.465 --> 00:44:24.090
is something that we
hear all the time,

00:44:24.090 --> 00:44:26.465
like, learn from your failures,
learn from your failures.

00:44:26.465 --> 00:44:30.600
And I know culturally at Google
this probably resonates well.

00:44:30.600 --> 00:44:34.519
You guys are exceptionally
well at just rapid iteration.

00:44:34.519 --> 00:44:36.560
But I think for the most
part, when we apply this

00:44:36.560 --> 00:44:40.730
to our lives, learn from your
failures translates into avoid

00:44:40.730 --> 00:44:43.610
failing, and then if
you do, just cover it

00:44:43.610 --> 00:44:45.027
up by saying I'm learning.

00:44:45.027 --> 00:44:47.110
And Craig takes a totally
different approach here.

00:44:47.110 --> 00:44:49.050
He says if you want
to get to something,

00:44:49.050 --> 00:44:52.330
you have to actually
seek out failure.

00:44:52.330 --> 00:44:53.954
And I'll let him do the talking.

00:44:53.954 --> 00:44:56.370
MALE SPEAKER: I wanted to go
into film when I was younger,

00:44:56.370 --> 00:44:59.170
but I didn't feel
like I had what

00:44:59.170 --> 00:45:00.765
it takes to become a filmmaker.

00:45:00.765 --> 00:45:06.745
I didn't feel like I could put
out my creativity out there.

00:45:06.745 --> 00:45:08.577
I didn't feel I had
the guts to do that.

00:45:08.577 --> 00:45:09.660
CRAIG BREWER: Interesting.

00:45:09.660 --> 00:45:12.850
MALE SPEAKER: So now I
feel like I could do it,

00:45:12.850 --> 00:45:15.020
but I guess that's
the main question

00:45:15.020 --> 00:45:17.150
for me is like-- one
of the main questions

00:45:17.150 --> 00:45:19.970
is, what are my fears?

00:45:19.970 --> 00:45:22.100
CRAIG BREWER: What
are some of them?

00:45:22.100 --> 00:45:25.710
MALE SPEAKER: Fear of failure
is definitely always there.

00:45:25.710 --> 00:45:29.290
CRAIG BREWER: Well, are you
perfectly clear on the fact

00:45:29.290 --> 00:45:30.860
that you will?

00:45:30.860 --> 00:45:32.560
Are you cool with that?

00:45:32.560 --> 00:45:36.236
I mean, you know that you're
going to fail repeatedly.

00:45:36.236 --> 00:45:37.130
MALE SPEAKER: Yeah.

00:45:37.130 --> 00:45:37.640
CRAIG BREWER: Yeah.

00:45:37.640 --> 00:45:38.800
I mean, it's going to happen.

00:45:38.800 --> 00:45:40.883
I mean, the only way that
you're going to get good

00:45:40.883 --> 00:45:41.570
is if you fail.

00:45:41.570 --> 00:45:46.110
So get to failing.

00:45:46.110 --> 00:45:48.889
Get that process going.

00:45:48.889 --> 00:45:50.430
Don't put that off
because it's going

00:45:50.430 --> 00:45:51.770
to hurt more when you're older.

00:45:51.770 --> 00:45:54.990
And what ends up
happening that I've seen

00:45:54.990 --> 00:45:57.250
is people don't want that hurt.

00:45:57.250 --> 00:45:59.610
And so they get
married, they have kids,

00:45:59.610 --> 00:46:02.340
and then they blame
their families

00:46:02.340 --> 00:46:04.300
and their circumstances
for the fact

00:46:04.300 --> 00:46:07.010
that they didn't want to fail.

00:46:07.010 --> 00:46:08.210
They didn't want to risk.

00:46:08.210 --> 00:46:11.030
They didn't want to
feel that kind of pain.

00:46:11.030 --> 00:46:18.140
So I say that if you want
that enrichment of success,

00:46:18.140 --> 00:46:21.790
then get busy failing
because it will happen.

00:46:25.310 --> 00:46:27.580
NATHAN GEBHARD: And when we
talk about which failures

00:46:27.580 --> 00:46:30.350
do you choose, I
think most of us

00:46:30.350 --> 00:46:33.710
think in this duality
of safe versus risk.

00:46:33.710 --> 00:46:36.630
And we had this great interview
with Jonathan Poneman.

00:46:36.630 --> 00:46:39.520
He was the founder
of Sub Pop Records.

00:46:39.520 --> 00:46:42.030
They covered anybody or
managed anybody from Nirvana

00:46:42.030 --> 00:46:43.610
all the way up to The Shins.

00:46:43.610 --> 00:46:49.160
And he said, if you look at
making decisions between safety

00:46:49.160 --> 00:46:51.760
and risk, the natural
inclination that we

00:46:51.760 --> 00:46:54.220
as humans have is to
protect and not to choose

00:46:54.220 --> 00:46:57.030
some risky things,
is to be safe.

00:46:57.030 --> 00:46:58.930
And he said the
way he approached

00:46:58.930 --> 00:47:01.180
life and the
perspective shift that

00:47:01.180 --> 00:47:02.840
enabled him to make
those decisions

00:47:02.840 --> 00:47:06.490
was to change the dynamic and
make the decisions not on what

00:47:06.490 --> 00:47:11.010
is safe or risky, but on what
is necessary versus unnecessary.

00:47:11.010 --> 00:47:13.880
For him, happiness
was necessary.

00:47:13.880 --> 00:47:16.610
For us, it might be our
family is necessary.

00:47:16.610 --> 00:47:19.490
Whatever it is that is
necessary versus unnecessary,

00:47:19.490 --> 00:47:22.950
it's a much easier way to
look at a yes or no decision,

00:47:22.950 --> 00:47:24.640
what things do you explore.

00:47:24.640 --> 00:47:27.140
Those things that give you life,
those things are necessary,

00:47:27.140 --> 00:47:31.590
versus worrying about
things that are risky.

00:47:31.590 --> 00:47:34.340
To leave you guys with
a challenge today,

00:47:34.340 --> 00:47:37.570
we thought just very simply,
reflect on your own roadmap.

00:47:37.570 --> 00:47:39.970
Reflect on the thing
that drives you,

00:47:39.970 --> 00:47:42.590
that the thing that you would
be happy doing no matter what,

00:47:42.590 --> 00:47:45.682
that foundational element
and those interests combined.

00:47:45.682 --> 00:47:47.390
If you were to shed
that noise and really

00:47:47.390 --> 00:47:49.590
think about how all of
that could come together

00:47:49.590 --> 00:47:54.260
in a dynamic way, very
simply just today,

00:47:54.260 --> 00:47:56.110
what's your adjacent possible?

00:47:56.110 --> 00:47:57.820
What's the small,
little thing that you

00:47:57.820 --> 00:48:00.094
could do today that just
gets you one step further?

00:48:00.094 --> 00:48:01.510
And it might be
that you're loving

00:48:01.510 --> 00:48:03.426
exactly what you're doing
now, but how can you

00:48:03.426 --> 00:48:04.510
take it further?

00:48:04.510 --> 00:48:06.260
Can you follow somebody
new on Twitter?

00:48:06.260 --> 00:48:07.950
Can you take a new class?

00:48:07.950 --> 00:48:11.700
Can you explore some interest
that you've never had?

00:48:11.700 --> 00:48:15.260
Whatever it is, break it down
into some baby, baby step,

00:48:15.260 --> 00:48:16.890
and just go for it.

00:48:16.890 --> 00:48:20.720
And to close it off,
before Q&amp;A-- this

00:48:20.720 --> 00:48:22.361
is how we closed the book.

00:48:22.361 --> 00:48:24.860
If you open up the book, this
is the last quote in the book.

00:48:24.860 --> 00:48:28.160
And rather than read it to you,
I'd rather her just share it.

00:48:28.160 --> 00:48:29.840
So this is Staceyann Chin.

00:48:29.840 --> 00:48:32.720
She's a poet and activist
we interviewed in New York.

00:48:32.720 --> 00:48:35.110
STACEYANN CHIN:
Attempt the impossible,

00:48:35.110 --> 00:48:40.910
do the crazy, stand
on a limb, and teeter.

00:48:40.910 --> 00:48:43.780
I say, teeter away.

00:48:43.780 --> 00:48:50.450
Reach, leap, attempt things that
everyone says can't be done.

00:48:50.450 --> 00:48:57.430
Run, jump, move, walk,
get your crazy done.

00:48:57.430 --> 00:49:00.910
You are your bravest self.

00:49:00.910 --> 00:49:04.610
And when I say brave, I
don't mean the quiet courage

00:49:04.610 --> 00:49:06.550
that it takes to raise a child.

00:49:06.550 --> 00:49:12.490
I mean the courage to do
what no one else is doing.

00:49:12.490 --> 00:49:15.930
These are the years
to climb a mountain.

00:49:15.930 --> 00:49:17.740
These are the years
to break an arm.

00:49:17.740 --> 00:49:19.800
These are the years
to fall in love

00:49:19.800 --> 00:49:24.160
and recover and fall in
love again and recover

00:49:24.160 --> 00:49:28.050
and to make love in
100 different cities

00:49:28.050 --> 00:49:32.620
and shave your head
and take a year off

00:49:32.620 --> 00:49:36.380
from your life to
do something that

00:49:36.380 --> 00:49:38.640
makes no sense to anyone else.

00:49:38.640 --> 00:49:42.486
Do it, do it, do it
now, and live it.

00:49:42.486 --> 00:49:43.860
If you want to
write, if you want

00:49:43.860 --> 00:49:45.550
to make films, anything
you want to do,

00:49:45.550 --> 00:49:48.180
you have to live to be
able to do it first.

00:49:48.180 --> 00:49:48.815
So live.

00:49:48.815 --> 00:49:50.680
Live, live, live, live.

00:49:50.680 --> 00:49:52.910
Get it out of your
system, so that when

00:49:52.910 --> 00:49:55.660
it is that you have
an ankle that is sore

00:49:55.660 --> 00:49:59.140
and you have bills
to pay, that there

00:49:59.140 --> 00:50:01.409
are no regrets behind you.

00:50:01.409 --> 00:50:03.950
The heaviest thing you will have
to carry as you move forward

00:50:03.950 --> 00:50:05.110
is regret.

00:50:05.110 --> 00:50:08.115
Make sure you're not
carrying too much.

