00:57:33.380 --> 00:57:36.090
I'll make a lateral move,
and then I'll move down.

00:57:36.090 --> 00:57:38.800
And he is ultimately the guy
that led all of the design work

00:57:38.800 --> 00:57:39.970
for all of Jordan shoes.

00:57:39.970 --> 00:57:42.030
And he's now the Vice
President of Innovation.

00:57:42.030 --> 00:57:44.785
And I think it's about
adjusting that level of risk

00:57:44.785 --> 00:57:45.910
for that time in your life.

00:57:45.910 --> 00:57:48.960
And certainly earlier and later,
there's those opportunities,

00:57:48.960 --> 00:57:51.050
particularly as it
relates to family,

00:57:51.050 --> 00:57:53.196
where you've got more latitude.

00:57:53.196 --> 00:57:54.820
And sometimes those
leaps can be bigger

00:57:54.820 --> 00:57:56.750
and sometimes they need
to be more incremental.

00:57:56.750 --> 00:57:57.200
JAMIE ZEHLER: Yeah.

00:57:57.200 --> 00:57:59.120
And one thought that I had
[? while ?] you were talking

00:57:59.120 --> 00:58:00.828
about that-- and it's
not so much related

00:58:00.828 --> 00:58:03.489
to risk-- but I think
working here and seeing all

00:58:03.489 --> 00:58:05.530
these interviews, one of
the big things I've seen

00:58:05.530 --> 00:58:09.057
is reevaluating how much you're
allowed to change who you are

00:58:09.057 --> 00:58:10.890
in your life and at
what age you're supposed

00:58:10.890 --> 00:58:11.848
to have it figured out.

00:58:11.848 --> 00:58:15.450
And so lots of people who've
gone back to school at 30, 40,

00:58:15.450 --> 00:58:19.030
50, and getting rid of
the noise that there's

00:58:19.030 --> 00:58:21.390
an expectation of at 20 you
have to have it figured out

00:58:21.390 --> 00:58:23.181
and that's who you are
for your whole life,

00:58:23.181 --> 00:58:25.172
and opening up the
possibility of like,

00:58:25.172 --> 00:58:26.880
it's OK to decide that
you're going to be

00:58:26.880 --> 00:58:29.570
somebody else at 40 or 50.

00:58:29.570 --> 00:58:32.652
And socially, I think that's not
really acceptable necessarily,

00:58:32.652 --> 00:58:35.110
but hearing it over and over
again from multiple people who

00:58:35.110 --> 00:58:38.740
have done it has, for me, broken
down the sense of one identity

00:58:38.740 --> 00:58:40.026
for your whole life.

00:58:40.026 --> 00:58:42.604
NATHAN GEBHARD: Pam Gaber is
a good story in that respect.

00:58:42.604 --> 00:58:43.395
JAMIE ZEHLER: Yeah.

00:58:43.395 --> 00:58:45.936
ALYSSA FRANK: Yeah, I think we
get so defined by our careers.

00:58:45.936 --> 00:58:48.610
I think when you go to a party
the question is, what do you

00:58:48.610 --> 00:58:49.680
do?

00:58:49.680 --> 00:58:56.050
And it's sort of the sole
source of our identity.

00:58:56.050 --> 00:58:59.430
But we all have this plethora
of interests that we pursue.

00:58:59.430 --> 00:59:02.260
And the things that we
might be most interested in

00:59:02.260 --> 00:59:05.430
isn't even the thing
we do 40 hours a week.

00:59:05.430 --> 00:59:08.590
But I think we live in
a time where there's

00:59:08.590 --> 00:59:12.569
unprecedented resources
to explore those things

00:59:12.569 --> 00:59:14.110
and cultivate those
little interests.

00:59:14.110 --> 00:59:18.720
YouTube tutorials,
lynda.com, there's

00:59:18.720 --> 00:59:23.180
just so many resources out
there to take little steps.

00:59:23.180 --> 00:59:24.880
And it doesn't have
to be a giant leap.

00:59:24.880 --> 00:59:29.820
But I think that those
iterative, little things, they

00:59:29.820 --> 00:59:32.899
accumulate over time and
can lead to [INAUDIBLE].

00:59:32.899 --> 00:59:34.940
NATHAN GEBHARD: Well,
thank you, guys, very much.

00:59:34.940 --> 00:59:35.540
Thanks, guys.

00:59:35.540 --> 00:59:37.690
